1isoZz-8859Zz-1-0&a=d&cl=CL1 titles A-Z]\n* F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885'' (2nd edition, Aldershot: Parliamentary Research Services, 1989)\n* Robert Waller, ''The [[Almanac of British Politics]]'' (1st edition, London: Croom Helm, 1983)\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180216152334/http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/edates.htm Politics Resources] (Election results from 1922 onwards)\n*[http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/flatfile.html Electoral Calculus] (Election results from 1955 onwards)\n*[http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7979/CBP-7979.pdf 2017 Election] House Of Commons Library 2017 Election report\n*[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/ A Vision Of Britain Through Time] (Constituency elector numbers)\n\n{{Constituencies in Wales}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Montgomeryshire (Uk Parliament Constituency)}}\n[[Category:Montgomeryshire]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in Mid Wales]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1536]]\n[[Category:Politics of Powys]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Montgomeryshire (Assembly constituency)}}\n{{coord|52.640|-3.469|display=title|region:GB_scale:100000}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency main\n |name        = Montgomeryshire\n |parliament  = uk\n |map1        = Montgomeryshire2007\n |map2        = \n |map_entity  = [[Wales]]\n |map_year    = \n |year        = 1542\n |abolished   = \n |type        = County\n |elects_howmany = One\n |previous    = [[Montgomery (UK Parliament constituency)|Montgomery]]\n |next        = \n |electorate  = 48,910 (December 2010)<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.statswales.wales.gov.uk/TableViewer/tableView.aspx?ReportId=14666|title=Beyond 20/20 WDS - Table view|date=1 December 2010|work=2011 Electorate Figures|publisher=StatsWales|accessdate=13 March 2011}}</ref>\n |mp          = [[Craig Williams (politician)|Craig Williams]]\n |party       = Conservative Party (UK)\n |region      = Wales\n |county      = [[Powys]]\n |european    = Wales\n |towns       = [[Newtown, Powys|Newtown]], [[Welshpool]]\n |national    = Mid and West Wales\n}}\n\n'''Montgomeryshire''' ({{lang-cy|Sir Drefaldwyn}}) is a [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] represented in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. Created in 1542, it elects one [[Member of Parliament]] (MP), traditionally known as the [[knight of the shire]], by the [[first-past-the-post]] system of election.\n\nThe [[Montgomeryshire (Assembly constituency)|Montgomeryshire Welsh Assembly constituency]] was created with the same boundaries in 1999.\n\n==Boundaries==\nThe seat is based on the ancient county of [[Montgomeryshire]], in the [[Subdivisions of Wales|principal area]] of [[Powys]]. One of [[United Kingdom|Britain]]'s most rural and isolated constituencies, Montgomeryshire elected Liberal or Liberal-affiliated candidates from 1880, until a Conservative victory in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]]. In the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]] it was only seat in England and Wales where a sitting Conservative MP was unseated, while nationally his party's seat majority increased. However, in 2010, the Conservatives won and held the seat in 2015 and 2017, with an increased majority. The seat is believed to be marginal, but the figures show that this is not the case. The seat was officially known as Montgomery before 1997. It is the only seat in Wales never to have elected a Labour MP. \n\nUntil 1918 this seat, in common with many others, contained an [[Montgomery (UK Parliament constituency)|enclaved seat]] which was comprised the boroughs of Montgomery, Llanfyllin, Llanidloes, Newtown and Welshpool. This seat survived the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]] which abolished many similar seats. The seat was finally abolished in 1918 and absorbed into the wider Montgomery seat where it remains today.\n\n===Proposed constituency changes===\nUnder proposed constituency boundary changes announced in September 2016, ahead of the next general election, the seat was to be partitioned, the northern half including Welshpool to be merged with [[Clwyd South (UK Parliament constituency)|Clwyd South]] to form a new seat of South Clwyd and North Montgomeryshire; most of the southern including Newtown will be merged with the [[Brecon and Radnor (UK Parliament constituency)|Brecon and Radnor seat]] to form a seat renamed as Brecon, Radnor and Montgomery,<ref>{{cite news|title=It's All Change For MPs, Political map to be transformed|work=Shropshire Star|date=13 September 2016|page=1}}Report by Mark Andrews.</ref> and the wards of Llanidloes and Blaen Hafren merged into the [[Ceredigion (UK Parliament constituency)|Ceredigion constituency]] which would form part of a new seat called Ceredigion and North Pembrokeshire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former MP urges re-think on move|work=Shropshire Star|date=17 September 2016|page=16}}Report based on criticism of proposals by former Montgomeryshire MP Delwyn Williams.</ref> However, the general elections of [[United Kingdom general election, 2017|2017]] and [[United Kingdom general election, 2019|2019]] were fought on existing boundaries.\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n\n===1542\u20131604===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Parliament!!Member\n|-\n|1542|| [[James Leche]]<ref name = HoP>{{cite web | url= http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/constituencies/montgomeryshire | title= History of Parliament| accessdate= 2011-08-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1545|| [[Humphrey Lloyd (by 1498-1562 or later)|Humphrey Lloyd]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1547|| [[Humphrey Lloyd (by 1498-1562 or later)|Humphrey Lloyd]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1553 (Mar)|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1553 (Oct)|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1554 (Apr)|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1554 (Nov)|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1555||''Not known''\n|-\n|1558|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert]]<ref name = HoP/>\n|-\n|1559 (Jan)|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert I]]<ref name = HoP2>{{cite web | url= http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/constituencies/montgomeryshire | title= History of Parliament| accessdate= 2011-08-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1562\u20131563|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert I]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1571|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert I]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1572|| [[John Price (died 1602)|John Price]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1584 (Oct)|| [[Richard Herbert (c.1557-1596)|Richard Herbert]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1586 (Oct)|| [[Oliver Lloyd (MP)|Oliver Lloyd]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1588 (Oct)|| [[Edward Herbert (died 1593)|Edward Herbert I]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1593|| [[Reginald Williams (MP)|Reginald WIlliams]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1597 (Sep)|| [[William Herbert, 1st Baron Powis|William Herbert]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|-\n|1601 (Oct)|| [[Edward Herbert, 1st Baron Herbert of Cherbury|Edward Herbert]]<ref name = HoP2/>\n|}\n\n===1604\u2013present===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Election!!Member<ref>{{Rayment-hc|m|3|date=March 2012}}</ref>!!Party\n|-\n|\n|1604\u20131611\n|[[William Herbert, 1st Baron Powis|William Herbert]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1614\n|[[William Herbert, 1st Baron Powis|William Herbert]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1621\u20131622\n| [[William Herbert, 1st Baron Powis|William Herbert]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1624\n| [[William Herbert, 1st Baron Powis|William Herbert]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1624\u20131629\n|[[William Herbert, 1st Baron Powis|William Herbert]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|[[Short Parliament|1640]]\n|[[Richard Herbert, 2nd Baron Herbert of Chirbury|Richard Herbert]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|[[Long Parliament|1640]]\u20131642\n|[[Sir John Pryce, 1st Baronet|John Pryce]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|''1642''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Seat vacant from 12 September 1642, when Pryce was disabled from sitting''\n|-\n|\n|1647\n| [[Edward Vaughan (of Llwydiarth)|Edward Vaughan]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1648\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Seat vacant after Vaughan was excluded in [[Pride's Purge]]''\n|-\n|\n|1653\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Not separately represented in the [[Barebones Parliament]]''\n|-\n|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1654\u20131655<br/>''(two members)''\n|[[Sir Charles Lloyd, 1st Baronet (of Garth)|Charles Lloyd]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|[[Sir John Pryce, 1st Baronet|John Pryce]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1656\u20131658<br/>''(two members)''\n|[[Sir Charles Lloyd, 1st Baronet (of Garth)|Charles Lloyd]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|[[Hugh Pryce]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1659\n| [[Edward Vaughan (of Llwydiarth)|Edward Vaughan]] \n||\n|-\n|\n|1660\n|[[John Purcell (MP)|John Purcell]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1661\n| [[Edward Vaughan (of Llwydiarth)|Edward Vaughan]]\n||\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1661\n|[[Andrew Newport|Hon. Andrew Newport]]\n|[[Tory|Conservative]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1679\n|[[Edward Vaughan (died 1718)|Edward Vaughan]]\n|[[Tory|Conservative]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" | \n|1719\n|[[Price Devereux, 10th Viscount Hereford|Hon. Price Devereux]]\n|[[Tory|Conservative]]\n|-\n|\n|1740\n|[[Robert Williams (died 1763)|Robert Williams]]\n||\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1741\n|[[Sir Watkin Williams-Wynn, 3rd Baronet|Sir Watkin Williams-Wynn]]\n|[[Tory|Conservative]]\n|-\n|\n|1742\n|[[Robert Williams (died 1763)|Robert Williams]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1747\n|[[Edward Kynaston (died 1772)|Edward Kynaston]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1772\n|[[Watkin Williams (1742\u20131808)|Watkin Williams]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1774\n|[[William Mostyn Owen]]\n||\n|-\n|\n|1795\n|[[Francis Lloyd (died 1799)|Francis Lloyd]]\n||\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/